# SpaceX Launches NASA’s Crew-10 Mission to the I.S.S.

After their flight was scrubbed on Wednesday, four astronauts successfully lifted off, which will allow two NASA astronauts to return to Earth after an unexpected extended stay in orbit.

[Learn more](https://help.nytimes.com/hc/en-us/articles/24318293692180)

Four astronauts launched on Friday en route to the International Space Station.

A SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket lifted off at 7:03 p.m. Eastern time from NASA’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida.

This is a routine rotation of crew on the space station, but it is garnering [extra attention](https://www.nytimes.com/2025/03/14/briefing/bringing-astronauts-home.html) because it will allow the return to Earth of [Suni Williams and Butch Wilmore](https://www.nytimes.com/2025/03/14/podcasts/the-daily/nasa-spacex-astronauts-iss-launch.html), two NASA astronauts whose brief scheduled visit to the space station last June was [unexpectedly stretched](https://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/17/science/nasa-boeing-starliner-astronauts.html) to more than nine months.

The stay of Ms. Williams and Mr. Wilmore in orbit was extended at least two more days when the first attempt at launching this mission on Wednesday was [called off](https://www.nytimes.com/2025/03/12/science/nasa-spacex-astronauts-iss-launch.html) with less than 45 minutes left in the countdown. Mission controllers were unable to solve a hydraulic issue with a clamp arm that holds onto the rocket until a few minutes before launch.

Based on the gathered evidence, here is the current situation regarding the number of people in space around March 29, 2025:

1. **Current and Planned Crew Movements:**
   - As of January 14, 2025, there were 10 humans in space.
   - SpaceX Crew-9 landed on March 18, 2025, which would have reduced the number of people in space.
   - SpaceX Crew-10 launched on March 14, 2025, with four astronauts, replacing Crew-9, maintaining the number of people in space.
   - There are no planned launches or landings that would change the number of people in space before March 29, 2025.

2. **Upcoming Missions:**
   - A Blue Origin New Shepard rocket is scheduled to launch with an all-female crew of six passengers on March 30, 2025, which is after the target date.
   - A SpaceX Dragon spacecraft is planned to launch on a crewed mission into polar orbit on March 31, 2025, which is also after the target date.
   - Soyuz MS-27 is scheduled to launch on April 8, 2025.

Given the information, the number of people in space is likely to remain at 10 until at least March 29, 2025, as there are no scheduled events that would reduce the number below 10 before that date.

FINAL PROBABILITY: 0.1
